s dependencies are fully resolved. This functionality is the responsibility of integration tests. Integration tests tend to be slower and more difficult to set up than unit tests, because they often depend on external dependencies and infrastructure. Thus, you should avoid testing things that could be tested with unit tests in integration tests. If you can test a given scenario with a unit test, you should test it with a unit test. If you can't, then consider using an integration test.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2557, 2558], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2557, 2558], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Integration tests will often have more complex setup and teardown procedures than unit tests. For example, an integration test that goes against an actual database will need a way to return the database to a known state before each test run. As new tests are added and the production database schema evolves, these test scripts will tend to grow in size and complexity. In many large systems, it is impractical to run full suites of integration tests on developer workstations before checking in changes to shared source control. In these cases, integration tests may be run on a build server.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Integration tests will often have more complex setup and teardown procedures than unit tests. For example, an integration test that goes against an actual database will need a way to return the database to a known state before each test run. As new tests are added and the production database schema evolves, these test scripts will tend to grow in size and complexity. In many large systems, it is impractical to run full suites of integration tests on developer workstations before checking in changes to shared source control. In these cases, integration tests may be run on a build server.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_open', tag='h2', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2559, 2560], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='##', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2559, 2560], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Functional tests', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Functional tests', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_close', tag='h2', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='##', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2561, 2562], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2561, 2562], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Integration tests are written from the perspective of the developer, to verify that some components of the system work correctly together. Functional tests are written from the perspective of the user, and verify the correctness of the system based on its requirements. The following excerpt offers a useful analogy for how to think about functional tests, compared to unit tests:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Integration tests are written from the perspective of the developer, to verify that some components of the system work correctly together. Functional tests are written from the perspective of the user, and verify the correctness of the system based on its requirements. The following excerpt offers a useful analogy for how to think about functional tests, compared to unit tests:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2563, 2564], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2563, 2564], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='"Many times the development of a system is likened to the building of a house. While this analogy isn\'t quite correct, we can extend it for the purposes of understanding the difference between unit and functional tests. Unit testing is analogous to a building inspector visiting a house\'s construction site. He is focused on the various internal systems of the house, the foundation, framing, electrical, plumbing, and so on. He ensures (tests) that the parts of the house will work correctly and safely, that is, meet the building code. Functional tests in this scenario are analogous to the homeowner visiting this same construction site. He assumes that the internal systems will behave appropriately, that the building inspector is performing his task. The homeowner is focused on what it will be like to live in this house. He is concerned with how the house looks, are the various rooms a comfortable size, does the house fit the family\'s needs, are the windows in a good spot to catch the morning sun. The homeowner is performing functional tests on the house. He has the user\'s perspective. The building inspector is performing unit tests on the house. He has the builder\'s perspective."', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='"Many times the development of a system is likened to the building of a house. While this analogy isn\'t quite correct, we can extend it for the purposes of understanding the difference between unit and functional tests. Unit testing is analogous to a building inspector visiting a house\'s construction site. He is focused on the various internal systems of the house, the foundation, framing, electrical, plumbing, and so on. He ensures (tests) that the parts of the house will work correctly and safely, that is, meet the building code. Functional tests in this scenario are analogous to the homeowner visiting this same construction site. He assumes that the internal systems will behave appropriately, that the building inspector is performing his task. The homeowner is focused on what it will be like to live in this house. He is concerned with how the house looks, are the various rooms a comfortable size, does the house fit the family\'s needs, are the windows in a good spot to catch the morning sun. The homeowner is performing functional tests on the house. He has the user\'s perspective. The building inspector is performing unit tests on the house. He has the builder\'s perspective."', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_open', tag='h2', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2565, 2566], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='##', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2565, 2566], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Source: Unit Testing versus Functional Tests', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Source: Unit Testing versus Functional Tests', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_close', tag='h2', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='##', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2567, 2568], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2567, 2568], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='I\'m fond of saying "As developers, we fail in two ways: we build the thing wrong, or we build the wrong thing." Unit tests ensure you are building the thing right; functional tests ensure you are building the right thing.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='I\'m fond of saying "As developers, we fail in two ways: we build the thing wrong, or we build the wrong thing." Unit tests ensure you are building the thing right; functional tests ensure you are building the right thing.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2569, 2570], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2569, 2570], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Since functional tests operate at the system level, they may require some degree of UI automation. Like integration tests, they usually work with some kind of test infrastructure as well. This 